Everything good on the Internet comes from old school bodybuilding forums and everything bad crawled out of SomethingAwful and /mu/.

I'm pretty sure bodybuilding spaces went under the radar for a long time and never got astroturfed by gov agencies like other spaces so they were able to develop a healthy culture. No one expects any dangerous discourse to come out of meatheads discussing chest exercises together

Like if female relatives have legitimately zero to worry about in life, they just start making up fake problems to get obsessed with, needing a new dishwasher or having to renovate some apartment room. Just unnecessary work they "have" to do. It legit works to keep them sane too.

Forgot who said aristocrats who suffered no financial struggles usually turned drug-degenerate, while ones who had to fight to retain their property  managed to "keep themselves together", but commoners are smarter because if they have no life problems they just invent fake ones.

It takes a genuinely insanely clearpilled man to be able to just enjoy life without any fake self-imposed struggle like doing ultra iron man marathons or whatever. Like Bruce Lee trapped in a room after a fight just sitting down and relaxing instead of hitting the door screaming.

People generally just refuse to accept it when you tell them that their problems are fake and I believe it's probably very rude to do so, but it's helpful to see it as an "isometrics workout" when one has no barbell to push on instead. Most ppl doing well just need fake troubles.

One 17th century English doctor wrote about a 120+ year old man, who was bedbound and had a hole on the wall next to his bed with a covering. He kept closing and opening it all day to keep the air at a certain degree of freshness. Like Tetris, but if you fail, you die of old age.

Like if it was closed for too long, the air got stuffy and smothering, if he kept it open too long he said it was too thin and cold, had to keep it at a perpetual balance. No idea how he slept. Maybe he didn't. That's how he lived so long. Sleep is the little death. Look it up.
